<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1861,2036]" box="[196,1330,1898,1924]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,359,1898,1924]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution:</emphasis>
Mexican endemic. The species occurs along Pacific coast from Sinaloa to Colima.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1861,2036]" box="[196,762,1935,1962]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,341,1935,1961]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Subspecies:</emphasis>
no subspecies have been described.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1861,2036]" lastBlockId="18.[151,1437,152,551]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,340,1973,1999]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Karyotype:</emphasis>
the karyotype is here described for the first time in this species. The karyotype shows 
<number box="[1382,1396,1973,1999]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
n = 
<number box="[151,183,2010,2036]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="26.0">26</number>
, with 
<number box="[254,283,2010,2036]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="12.0">12</number>
macro- and 
<number box="[431,460,2010,2036]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="14.0">14</number>
microchromosomes (
<figureCitation box="[715,803,2010,2036]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,254,1088,1112]" captionTargetBox="[280,1314,645,1021]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[231,1356,607,1067]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Karyotype of Plestiodon parvulus male (2 n = 26)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196016/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[770,803,2010,2036]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). All the macro-chromosomes are biarmed as are four pairs of the microchromosomes. The other microchromosomes are telocentric. This karyotype differs in the morphology of the microchromosomes from other karyotypes of 
<taxonomicName box="[972,1106,189,214]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Plestiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[972,1106,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Plestiodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. For example, the microchromosomes seem all biarmed in 
<taxonomicName box="[627,802,226,251]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Plestiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inexpectatus">
<emphasis box="[627,802,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. inexpectatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Caputo et al. 1994" authorityName="Caputo et al." authorityYear="1994" box="[859,1246,226,252]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Plestiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obsoletus">
<emphasis box="[859,999,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. obsoletus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Caputo" box="[1014,1236,226,252]" pageId="18" pageNumber="26" refString="Caputo, V., Odierna, G. &amp; Aprea, G. (1994) A chromosomal study of Eumeces and Scincus, primitive members of the Scincidae (Reptilia, Squamata). Bolletino di Zoologia, 61, 155 - 162." type="journal article" year="1994">
Caputo 
<emphasis box="[1108,1166,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1173,1236,226,252]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,152,551]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,400,263,289]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[196,259,263,289]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">DNA</collectionCode>
taxonomy:
</emphasis>
neither gene sequence of 
<taxonomicName box="[708,840,264,289]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Plestiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvulus">
<emphasis box="[708,840,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. parvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is present in GenBank. Therefore, the fragment of the 
<number box="[195,225,301,327]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="16.0">16</number>
S rRNA sequenced for this study was aligned with available sequences of other congeners (
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz" pageId="18" pageNumber="29" refString="Schmitz, A., Mausfeld, P. &amp; Embert, D. (2004) Molecular studies on the genus Eumeces Wiegmann, 1834: phylogenetic relationships and taxonomic implications. Hamadryad, 28, 73 - 89." type="journal article" year="2004">
Schmitz 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[191,254,338,364]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) to assess the phylogenetic affinities and genetic distance of this species within the genus. The obtained tree is shown in 
<figureCitation box="[472,594,376,402]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[151,256,1293,1317]" captionTargetBox="[294,1315,394,1256]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[231,1356,381,1272]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11. Neighbour-Joining tree of 16 S rDNA haplotypes (518 bp) of Plestiodon species. Bootstrap values (%) obtained by the NJ, ML and MP are shown. The substitution model selected for ML was the Generalised time reversible (GTR) model with rate variation among sites (+ G), a proportion of invariable sites I = 0.5020 and a gamma distribution shape parameter of 0.3681." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196017/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Figure 
<number box="[561,594,376,402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
. The results suggest that 
<taxonomicName box="[909,1053,376,401]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Plestiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvulus">
<emphasis box="[909,1053,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">E. parvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the sister species of another Mexican endemic species, 
<emphasis box="[472,560,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. l y n x e</emphasis>
(bootstrap values 
<number box="[784,814,413,439]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="71.0">71</number>
% with NJ and 
<number box="[999,1029,413,439]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="58.0">58</number>
% with ML). The genetic distance between the two species is 4.5–5.0% and is among the lowest interspecific genetic distance of the analysed dataset. This is the first report of a relationship between these two species (
<bibRefCitation author="Griffith" box="[1033,1261,488,514]" pageId="18" pageNumber="27" refString="Griffith, H., Ngo, A. &amp; Murphy R. W. A. (2000) A Cladistic evaluation of the cosmopolitan genus Eumeces Wiegmann (Reptilia, Squamata, Scincidae). Russian Journal of Herpetology, 7, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="2000">
Griffith 
<emphasis box="[1132,1192,488,513]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1199,1261,488,514]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz" pageId="18" pageNumber="29" refString="Schmitz, A., Mausfeld, P. &amp; Embert, D. (2004) Molecular studies on the genus Eumeces Wiegmann, 1834: phylogenetic relationships and taxonomic implications. Hamadryad, 28, 73 - 89." type="journal article" year="2004">
Schmitz 
<emphasis box="[1377,1436,488,513]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[151,215,525,551]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
